title: Telegram typing indicator should be driven by real session activity, not wrapper-local refresh loops
---
Refined from live investigation and code review (including Codex background task 16). The current Telegram typing indicator is not reliably coupled to actual agent non-idle state. Live symptoms observed: bot can appear typing while idle, fail to show typing while actively working, then later show typing again while active. Code analysis found typing is controlled mainly by wrapper-local loops in `src/telegram.ml` that periodically resend `sendChatAction`, with direct-turn and deferred/autonomous wrappers starting/stopping typing based on wrapped promise lifetime rather than a single authoritative session activity model. Important details from the investigation: (1) typing starts only on certain Telegram LLM paths and does not cover all real work phases (for example some command paths, media preprocessing before the turn, etc.); (2) typing is kept alive by periodic refresh plus some local post-send refresh calls; (3) typing stops when the wrapper promise resolves, not when an explicit session-level idle transition occurs; (4) busy/queued-session behavior means inbound messages can queue with no immediate typing while previous work continues, so the visible typing can reflect wrapper lifetime or queue-drain behavior rather than the user’s intuitive notion of “agent is currently working on this session now”; (5) autonomous continuation/deferred wrappers add further phase shifts. Goal: redesign Telegram typing so it is a projection of real session activity / non-idle state, not an incidental side-effect of whichever wrapper currently owns the refresh loop. Acceptance criteria: (a) typing is shown while the session is genuinely active across LLM work, tool execution, queued-drain work, and autonomous continuation when appropriate; (b) typing stops promptly when the session becomes idle; (c) typing does not remain stale-on while idle; (d) typing does not disappear during active work because a wrapper ended early or a work phase was not covered; (e) implementation is driven by a clearer session/activity state model, with Telegram transport using that state rather than defining it; (f) tests or bounded verification cover the main lifecycle transitions; (g) any remaining intentionally uncovered phases are documented explicitly.